abstract: The ice in the West Branch of the Susquehauna was in motion generally yesterday, but, with the exception of the gorges about Lock Haven, no complete break-up has occured. From Lock Haven to Williamsport the river is pretty clear of ice, the high water on the dams at both these places permitting the ice to pass over them without hindrance. The Glen Union ice moved some distance, but jammed again.

abstract: The arrangements for the dedication of the new Masonic Temple, corner of Sixth avenue and Twenty third street, which is announced to take place Wednesday, June 2, are steadily progressing. abstract: ROCHESTER, N.Y., April 2.--The Commissioners of Water-works are urged on every band to resign. Under no circumstances will the people stand trifling or whitewash.

Assistant Pastor Halliday made his first appearance since his recent severe illness.

abstract: NEW-HAVEN, April 2.--Music Hall was crowded to-night to its atmost capacity with the awakened Repulicans of New-Haven, who had been got together without the help of cheap music and fireworks. abstract: WASHINGTON, April 4--1 A. M.--Cloudy and cool weather continues, with light rain, on the New-England and Middle Atlantic coasts. Generally clear weather prevails in the remaining districts, with light to gentle winds and slight rise of temperature, except in the South Atlantic States. The Allegheny, the Ohio, the Central Mississippi, and the Arkansas Rivers have risen.

abstract: The strike of the Cuban journeymen cigarmakers still continues, but like all similar strikes seems destined to a brief career. Mr. Lierena, Secretary of the Cuban Cigar Manufacturers' Association, stated yesterday that by the time the manufacturers required employes the strike would be at an end. Nearly all of the manufacturers have large stocks of cigars on hand, owing to the dull season and the small demand for high-priced cigars.

At present the traffic in freight is not sufficient to cover the expenses of running the regular trips, but the managers of all the principal lines state that they are still sending out the usual number of steamers.

abstract: ALBANY, N.Y., April 8. The Assembly in Committee of the Whole to-night, before a full attendance of members, and galleries and lobby filled with spectators, took up for consideration the General Excise bill, as reported by the minoriy from the Committee on Internal Affairs, and after a brief debate on amendments without any important results progressed the bill. Subsequently the majority and minority Excise bills were made the special order for next Thursday evening.

abstract: WASHINGTON, April 27.--Hundreds of persons remained at the scene of yesterday's railroad catastrophe until daylight this morning, watching the operations of the wreckers in removing the shattered care and locomotives, and supposing that there were bodies of victims in the rains yet to be discovered. All who here seriously wounded, however. had been carried to their homes or the Providence Hospital soon after the accident.
